y, Knowledge and Power in Europe's Encounter with Islam</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H04681X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research aims to make an original contribution to the growing literature on religion in international politics by exploring:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>How the secular contributes to shaping contemporary understandings of subjectivity, knowledge and power&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>How these understandings account for Europe's conflictual encounter with Islam&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>How this conflict may be defused by postsecular forms of dialogue-based engagement between Europe and Islam. &lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>Focusing on whether, how and to what extent, and at what risk for its cohesion and identity should a secular community accept, authorise or even support political expressions of belief, this research engages with cutting-edges debates such as multiculturalism and the integration of Muslim minorities in Europe, religious fundamentalism, the question of the Christian roots of Europe, and the role and limits of religion in the public sphere. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>While theoretically grounded in social and political thought and in the theory of international relations, this work also offers the first systematic empirical investigation of the most heated controversies that have surrounded Muslims in Europe: &lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>The Rushdie Affair.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>The headscarf ban in France. &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>The 'Danish Cartoons'.&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>The speech of Pope Benedict XVI at the University of Regensburg.&lt;/li>
